ted Kingdom":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1321–1378":"about 1321–1378","1321–1378":"1321–1378","1319–1368":"1319–1368","1346–Male":"1346–Deceased","1348–Female":"1348–Deceased","1295–1352":"1295–1352","1292–Female":"1292–Deceased","7 March 1352":"7 March 1352","Cir 1368":"1368","1352":"1352","Abt 1346":"about 1346","1295":"1295","1292":"1292","1348":"1348","1346":"1346","1368":"1368","1378":"1378","Abt 1321":"about 1321","1321":"1321","about 1348":"about 1348","about 1344":"about 1344","1319":"1319","Devonport, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devonport, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Cobham, Surrey, England":"Cobham, Surrey, England","Giddecote, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Giddecote, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Dabernon was born about 1321, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir John d'Abernon, was 28 and her mother, Joan Giffard, was 30. She married John Dennis about 1344, in Devonport, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1378, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 58."},"et":{"Abt 1321–1378":"umbes 1321–1378","1321–1378":"1321–1378","1319–1368":"1319–1368","1346–Male":"1346–Surnud","1348–Female":"1348–Surnud","1295–1352":"1295–1352","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","7 March 1352":"7. märts 1352","Cir 1368":"1368","1352":"1352","Abt 1346":"umbes 1346","1295":"1295","1292":"1292","1348":"1348","1346":"1346","1368":"1368","1378":"1378","Abt 1321":"umbes 1321","1321":"1321","about 1348":"umbes 1348","about 1344":"umbes 1344","1319":"1319","Devonport, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devonport, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cobham, Surrey, England":"Cobham, Surrey, England","Giddecote, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Giddecote, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1321–1378":"noin 1321–1378","1321–1378":"1321–1378","1319–1368":"1319–1368","1346–Male":"1346–Kuollut","1348–F